  "text": "Apache Kafka implements a comprehensive service lifecycle management pattern for its Connect runtime. The architecture follows a hierarchical service initialization and coordinated shutdown pattern.\n\n**Core Lifecycle Architecture:**\n\nThe lifecycle pattern is built around the `Herder` interface (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/Herder.java), which defines `start()` and `stop()` methods. This interface represents the main service coordinator that manages all components of a Kafka Connect worker.\n\n**Lifecycle Orchestration Layers:**\n\n1. **Top-Level Orchestrator (Connect.java)**: The `Connect` class serves as the primary entry point, managing the lifecycle of three key components:\n   - The Herder (coordinator of connectors/tasks)\n   - REST server for the control plane\n   - A shutdown hook for graceful shutdown\n   \n   Startup sequence: `herder.start()` → `rest.initializeResources()`\n   Shutdown sequence: `rest.stop()` → `herder.stop()` (reverse order)\n\n2. **Herder Implementation Hierarchy:**\n   - **AbstractHerder** (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/AbstractHerder.java): Provides the base lifecycle management with `startServices()` and `stopServices()` template methods.\n   - **DistributedHerder** (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/distributed/DistributedHerder.java): Extends AbstractHerder with distributed coordination.\n\n**Service Initialization Sequence (Forward):**\n\nIn `AbstractHerder.startServices()` (lines 180-184):\n1. `this.worker.start()` - Initializes the worker that runs connectors and tasks\n2. `this.statusBackingStore.start()` - Starts the status storage service\n3. `this.configBackingStore.start()` - Starts the configuration storage service\n\nIn `DistributedHerder.run()` (lines 376-403), after startServices():\n1. Reads to the end of internal topics\n2. Joins the consumer group\n3. Waits for initial rebalance\n4. Begins processing external requests and rebalance events\n\n**Service Shutdown Sequence (Reverse Order):**\n\nIn `AbstractHerder.stopServices()` (lines 186-192):\n1. `this.statusBackingStore.stop()` - Stops status storage (first dependency)\n2. `this.configBackingStore.stop()` - Stops configuration storage\n3. `this.worker.stop()` - Stops the worker (last, was started first)\n4. `this.connectorExecutor.shutdown()` - Shuts down executor service\n5. Closes connector client config override policy plugin\n\nIn `DistributedHerder.stop()` (lines 852-862):\n1. Sets stopping flag\n2. Wakes up group member\n3. Shuts down herderExecutor with graceful timeout\n4. Shuts down forwardRequestExecutor\n5. Shuts down startAndStopExecutor\n\nIn `DistributedHerder.closeResources()` (lines 838-842):\n1. Stops worker group member\n2. Closes herder metrics\n3. Closes any custom resources managed via uponShutdown\n\n**Backing Store Lifecycle (Storage Interfaces):**\n\nThree backing store interfaces follow the standard lifecycle pattern:\n\n- **OffsetBackingStore** (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/storage/OffsetBackingStore.java): Manages connector offsets\n  - Implementations: KafkaOffsetBackingStore, FileOffsetBackingStore, MemoryOffsetBackingStore\n  \n- **ConfigBackingStore** (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/storage/ConfigBackingStore.java): Manages connector and task configurations\n  - Implementations: KafkaConfigBackingStore, MemoryConfigBackingStore\n  \n- **StatusBackingStore** (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/storage/StatusBackingStore.java): Manages connector and task status information\n  - Implementations: KafkaStatusBackingStore, MemoryStatusBackingStore\n\nAll backing stores follow the pattern where `start()` initializes resources and `stop()` performs graceful shutdown. For example, KafkaOffsetBackingStore.start() (line 231) initializes the KafkaBasedLog for reading/writing offsets.\n\n**REST Server Lifecycle:**\n\nThe `RestServer` class (connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/rest/RestServer.java) manages the HTTP control plane:\n- `initializeServer()`: Starts the Jetty server and initializes handlers\n- `stop()`: Gracefully shuts down handlers, REST extensions, and the Jetty server with a 60-second timeout\n\n**Key Design Patterns:**\n\n1. **Dependency Ordering**: Services are started in order of their dependencies, and stopped in reverse order. This ensures dependent services are ready before dependents are initialized.\n\n2. **Graceful Shutdown**: Shutdown operations use configurable timeouts (e.g., GRACEFUL_SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT_MS = 60 seconds in RestServer) to allow in-flight requests to complete.\n\n3. **Coordinated Shutdown**: DistributedHerder coordinates shutdown across distributed nodes using the group membership protocol, ensuring proper cleanup.\n\n4. **Lifecycle Hooks**: `startServices()` and `stopServices()` serve as extension points for subclasses to customize initialization/shutdown.\n\n5. **Resource Cleanup**: The `uponShutdown` list in DistributedHerder allows external components to register cleanup actions that execute at shutdown time.\n\n**MirrorMaker Integration:**\n\nMirrorMaker (connect/mirror/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/mirror/MirrorMaker.java) demonstrates the lifecycle pattern at a higher level, managing multiple herders and coordinating their startup/shutdown.\n\nThis lifecycle management ensures that Kafka Connect can reliably initialize complex, distributed systems while guaranteeing that all resources are properly cleaned up during shutdown, preventing resource leaks and data loss."
